What I was getting at is I don't think the Rules need to intrude upon
personal agreements at all, especially insofar as Orders are concerned.
I'm only recognizing the mechanism in my Order fix because it is in
place and its existence should be subject to a separate debate.

Why is there a need for this?  I think this game is intimate enough that
the social sanctions for flouting an agreement are much more effective
than any "legal" enforcements. . .  I really suspect that this segment
of the rules will lay dormant until some misunderstanding erupts between
a few players and the issue gets dragged into the courts.  Such an event
would probably so acid and nasty that it would immediately result in
loud calls for the repeal of this whole "personal agreement" structure.

I think that the only "agreements" that the Rules should recognize are
those "agreements" that are structured in the Rules themselves.  The
existing law is so loose that it is quite possible that a number of
players have already entered into legally binding agreements without
realizing it. I don't think this is a Good Thing.

Swann
