Actually, I think Swann and I are on the same wavelength here.  Either keep
personal agreements and their enforcement totally on a meta-game level, or
bring them totally under the scope of the Rules, so it is clear that the
authority of such agreements to compell action (or inaction) comes from the
Rules.  While I don't have Swann's (apparent) preference as to which way to go
with this, I do agree that the half-way position we seem to have now is not a
Good Thing.

BTW, I use "meta-game" here to mean outside the Rules, but not necessarily
outside of in-game ("role-playing") activity.  Maybe I'm misusing the term, and
I should use some other terminology for a "Rule/extra-Rule" dichotomy that is
orthogonal to the "game/meta-game" dichotomy?

-- Crito

